Behçet syndrome / Behcet disease

#2021GM-NOV Q26

[!INFO] Behcet's disease main features: PATHERGY TEST


Chronic systemic inflammation
Unknown etiology.
unique for involvement of vessels of all sizes!

[!INFO] The single most important clinical finding
Most important clinical manifestation is recurrent mucocutaneous ulcers.

  • painful, oral and genital ulcers are almost universal. Most common presenting complaints.
  • Scrotum / major and minor labia.
  • They occur in the first few years. Can cause scarring.
  • Erythema nodosum and erythema multiforme , superficial thrombophlebitis can occur.
  • Occular disease:
    • Posterior (most common) or pan uveitisi, retinal vasculitis
  • Assymetric oligoarthritis, medium to large lesions.
  • unsually, veins are more commonly affected than arteries:
    • Budd chiari syndrome
    • Cerebral venous thrombosis
    • venous thrombosis
    • SVC and IVC
    • pulmonary artery aneurysm are somewhat specific for behcets but are rare.
  • Neurologic compliations:
    • Encephalitis, cranial nerve palsies, ataxia and myelopathy.
  • GI pathology:
    • Ulcers in the ileoceoal region similar appearance to Crohn's disease.
  • Malaise, fatigue and periodic fevers.

Presents between 20 and 40 years old.
"Silk road disease" - europe, persia, india china. Turkey has x 100 the incidence.

It is a clinical diagnosis. There is no confirmatory tests.
Pathergy test: Development of a papule or pustule-like lesion 48 hours after skin prick by 20 guage needle.

Behcets disease: treatment

Attack rate

the "proportion of those who become ill after a specified exposure over a specified time period"
Or
The "proportion of exposed people who become ill".

1. *Live attenuated* influenza - (also contraindicated in close contacts / caregivers of immunosuppressed patients!)
1. *Live attenuated* influenza vaccine (NOT the killed IV vaccine)

Varicella zoster vaccination

Varicella zoster is a highly infectious virus transmitted through inhalation of aerosolized droplets. Initially presents as upper airway infection which enters the circulation in 2 - 3 days. Second bout of viraemia occurs in 10-12 days when it presents with the rash.
Rash begins on face and trunk and spreads outwards to extremities.
Resolves in 4 - 7 days.

Varicella zoster immunoglobulin

It reduces the severity and attack rate of primary varicella.

Indications

Should be given

  • immediately (upto 10 days) after exposure to immunocompromised patients.
  • Pregnant women lacking evidence of immunity.
  • Newborns who's mothers develop signs of varicella between 5 days before and 2 days after delivery. Mnemonic: "5b4 and 2da"
  • premature newborns whose mother don't have immunity to varicella.

Influenza vaccine

The vaccine is made by

  • Cell culture methods
  • Egg based flu vaccine (can produce live attenuated and killed vaccines)
  • Recombinant vaccines.

The live attenuated influenza vaccines are given via nasal spray. They care contraindicated in pregnancy and ?immunosuppressed people.
The killed vaccine the one given IV.
